## Design decisions locked

**D1 — TOTP library: otplib v12**
`otplib` v12 — RFC 6238 compliant, actively maintained, ESM-compatible. Imported
as `import { authenticator } from 'otplib'`. Issuer string: `"School Kit"`.

**D2 — Cookie strategy (D2 from pre-build locks)**
The Next.js route handler at `apps/web/src/app/api/auth/[...auth]/route.ts` is the
only path that sets or clears the `sk_session` cookie. It proxies POST requests for
`login`, `signup-owner`, `logout`, `2fa/challenge` (and GET for `me`) to the NestJS
API. On success it sets:

```
Set-Cookie: sk_session=<rawToken>; HttpOnly; Secure; SameSite=Lax; Path=/
```

`Secure` is `false` in localhost dev (`process.env.NODE_ENV !== 'production'`).

The Next.js `middleware.ts` reads only cookie **presence** to gate `/(admin)/` and
`/(teacher)/` route groups — no DB call, no session validation. Actual session
validation remains in NestJS `AuthGuard`. The middleware is stateless and fast.

**D3 — In-memory token; no localStorage**
The raw bearer token is:
- Stored in a module-level `let activeToken: string | null = null` in `api-client.ts`
- Exported via `setActiveToken(token)` — called by the auth-provider after login/signup
- Read by `apiFetch` instead of `window.localStorage`
- Never written to localStorage, sessionStorage, or any persistent client store

Cold-boot hydration: the auth-provider calls the Next.js proxy `GET /api/auth/me`,
which reads the `sk_session` cookie server-side, forwards to NestJS as
`Authorization: Bearer <cookie-value>`, and returns `{ user, school, roles,
permissions, token }`. The `token` in the response body allows the auth-provider
to seed `activeToken` for the in-memory Bearer header on subsequent NestJS calls.

Security gain: the token never touches localStorage (which survives tab close and
is readable by XSS scripts long after the page is gone). In-memory state is gone
on reload; the HttpOnly cookie re-hydrates it transparently.

**D4 — 2FA login challenge flow (D4 from pre-build locks)**
When `POST /auth/login` resolves a user with `totp_enabled = true`:
- Does NOT issue a session
- Generates `challengeToken = crypto.randomBytes(32).toString('base64url')`
- Writes `2fa:challenge:<challengeToken>` → `JSON.stringify({ userId, schoolId })`
  to Redis with TTL = 300 seconds
- Returns HTTP 200 `{ requiresTwoFactor: true, challengeToken }` — no `user`, no
  `school`, no `token` in this branch

`POST /auth/2fa/challenge` (throttled: 5 req / 5min per-IP):
- Reads `2fa:challenge:<challengeToken>` from Redis
- Deletes the key immediately (single-use; replay impossible)
- `withTenant(schoolId)` to fetch `totp_secret`
- `totpService.verifyCode(totp_secret, code)` — rejects on wrong code or expired challenge
- On success: issues a normal session, returns
  `{ requiresTwoFactor: false, user, school, token }` (same shape as normal login)

**D5 — TOTP secret storage (D5 from pre-build locks)**
`totp_secret TEXT NULL` — active TOTP secret (NULL when 2FA not enabled).
`totp_pending_secret TEXT NULL` — setup in progress (cleared on confirm or on a new
setup call). `totp_enabled BOOLEAN NOT NULL DEFAULT false`.
TOTP secrets contain no PII and no key material that helps an attacker without the
secret itself. Protection: never returned in list responses or logs; the
`POST /auth/2fa/setup` response is the only path that surfaces the secret (to
the owner, at enrollment time). Never logged.

**D6 — RedisService injectable**
A thin `RedisService` (`apps/api/src/common/redis/redis.service.ts`) wraps an
IORedis client (IORedis is already a transitive dep via BullMQ). Registered in a
`@Global() RedisModule`. Provides `get`, `set(key, value, ttlSeconds)`, `del`,
`getAndDel` (atomic GET + DEL via a Lua one-liner). Used exclusively for the 2FA
challenge store. `QueueModule` continues to manage its own IORedis connections
separately (BullMQ isolates connections per queue/worker).

**D7 — Permissions on 2FA management endpoints**
`POST /auth/2fa/setup`, `POST /auth/2fa/confirm`, `DELETE /auth/2fa`:
`@Permissions('auth.2fa.manage')` — owner-only (from CP1 seed).
`GET /auth/2fa/status`: `@Permissions('auth.2fa.read')` — owner + admin can check
2FA status; only the owner can enroll.
`POST /auth/2fa/challenge`: public — no `AuthGuard`, no `PermissionsGuard`
(it IS the login completion step; session not yet issued).

**D8 — LoginResponse discriminated union**
```ts
// packages/types/src/auth/login.dto.ts
export type LoginResponse =
  | { requiresTwoFactor: false; user: SignupOwnerUserDto; school: SignupOwnerSchoolDto; token: string }
  | { requiresTwoFactor: true; challengeToken: string };
```
Existing non-2FA login tests use the `requiresTwoFactor: false` branch — they
type-narrow correctly. Auth-provider `login()` type-narrows on `requiresTwoFactor`
before calling `meRequest()` (no session exists on the `true` branch).

**D9 — /settings/security is owner-only; /settings link added**
A `RequirePermission('auth.2fa.manage')` guard at the page level. The settings hub
`/settings/page.tsx` gets a "Security" card linking to `/settings/security`.
`react-qr-code` for QR rendering (pure SVG, no canvas).

